<form id="quiz-form">
  <h2>Question 1: What is your favorite color?</h2>
  <label>
    <input type="radio" name="question1" value="red"> Red
  </label>
  <label>
    <input type="radio" name="question1" value="blue"> Blue
  </label>
  <label>
    <input type="radio" name="question1" value="green"> Green
  </label>

  <h2>Question 2: What is your favorite animal?</h2>
  <label>
    <input type="radio" name="question2" value="dog"> Dog
  </label>
  <label>
    <input type="radio" name="question2" value="cat"> Cat
  </label>
  <label>
    <input type="radio" name="question2" value="bird"> Bird
  </label>

  <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form>
In this example:

Each question is enclosed in an <h2> heading element for clarity.
Each set of radio buttons for a question shares the same name attribute to ensure that the user can only select one option for each question. For example, name="question1" for Question 1 and name="question2" for Question 2.
The value attribute of each radio button represents the user's choice for that option.
You can further enhance this form by adding JavaScript to handle form submission and collect user choices, or you can use server-side processing to handle the form data, depending on your specific requirements.






    
<script>
  document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
    document.getElementById('order-form').addEventListener('submit', function(e) {
      e.preventDefault(); // Prevent the form from submitting normally

      // Get the selected product value
      const selectedProduct = document.querySelector('input[name="product"]:checked').value;

      // Redirect to the order details page with the selected product value
      window.location.href = '/checkout?product=' + selectedProduct;
    });
  });
</script>


